*JP:* Great to be here. Thanks Ben for having me.

*From my perspective, this interview is really going to be a learning sessi=
on for me, about Rescale, about high-performance computing. A spot I don=E2=
=80=99t know a ton about, to be totally honest. So I want you to educate me=
. But I want to start with you, tell me about your background starting in t=
he Netherlands.*

*JP:* Yeah, absolutely. So that=E2=80=99s where the name Joris comes from. =
Originally born in the Netherlands, my parents are both very Dutch, both ac=
ademics and I grew up in a pretty, I would say, middle-class kind of lifest=
yle. We moved around a lot as my mom was a professor in dentistry.

I learned at a very early age to program, and that=E2=80=99s where I would =
say my tech story really started, is my dad was a big Steve Jobs fan, so wh=
en I was around seven years old is probably when I first started doing a li=
ttle programming in this application called Logo ( https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Logo_(programming_language) ) on the Mac, the first kind of Mac, just=
 moving a cursor around drawing pictures. But quickly, that turned into =E2=
=80=94 we actually moved to Australia when I was a teenager and I learned o=
bject-oriented programming on the NeXT computers. So we were, I don=E2=80=
=99t know how my dad convinced my mom, but we were a very early adopter of =
the NeXT computer.

*That is a hardcore Steve Jobs fan. Didn=E2=80=99t just have a Mac but then=
 had to go buy a NeXT as well.*

*JP:* Exactly! The NeXT was a really special computer far ahead of its time=
. It pulled forward some technologies, had an optical drive, things like th=
at, so this was in the 90s. It was advanced enough that we had folks from t=
he university that would come run email servers and things like that out of=
 our house. We wired up our house with ethernet, and so that gave me a fun =
experience and just really experiencing the Internet the first time.

NeXT computer is also, I don=E2=80=99t know if you know but Steve Jobs was =
good friends with Stephen Wolfram ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephen_W=
olfram ) and Mathematica came with the NeXT Cube ( https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Wolfram_Mathematica ) and so that also started a lot of my interest i=
n applied math, which later, as Steve Jobs would say, =E2=80=9CYou can conn=
ect the dots backwards=E2=80=9D, right?

Mathematica, if you=E2=80=99re not familiar with it, is a very, very advanc=
ed tool. So we=E2=80=99re probably more familiar with things like MATLAB ( =
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MATLAB ). Mathematica is built for math PhDs,=
 but I was as a teenager using that to do my math homework very quickly and=
 easily.

*Nice. That=E2=80=99s amazing because usually you would think that you woul=
d be into math and then were into Mathematica. But you being, =E2=80=9COh, =
this is neat, Mathematica. What is it actually used for?=E2=80=9D, it=E2=80=
=99s like you went the opposite direction.*

*JP:* Exactly. And actually with Mathematica, you could draw and the handbo=
ok had these beautiful tetrahedron kind of shapes and things like that and =
so yeah, I got really excited about the math capabilities.

But ultimately, the Internet changed everything. Then Netscape came about, =
we started using a lot of this kind of intranet capabilities at home with t=
he university and eventually just standard Internet stuff. Message boards, =
chat rooms, ICQ, all that stuff, and became really passionate about compute=
rs, learned with the programming skills to build things on computers. I thi=
nk that also was something I learned really from both of my parents.

But building things is really satisfying, whether that=E2=80=99s in a wood =
shop, building something physically, or to building programs. I think again=
, connecting backwards, I would say if it=E2=80=99s obvious, then entrepren=
eurship makes sense. At the time, I never really thought about companies. I=
t was just enjoyed building programs, things to do stuff at school. It was =
interesting that you take these projects to school, they would never believ=
e that you did it yourself. So you=E2=80=99d have these programs, you=E2=80=
=99d come to the science fair and I remember that my project was disqualifi=
ed because it was too advanced, =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s no way a kid built=
 this=E2=80=9D.

*You need to go back retroactively and demand a change. Say, =E2=80=9CLook,=
 I=E2=80=99ve demonstrated I could have done this.=E2=80=9D*

*JP:* Yeah, that=E2=80=99s exactly right. But yeah, that was the early days=
 experiences and then in college, I moved to the US, I went to University o=
f Michigan.

*What did you study there?*

*JP:* I studied applied math and mechanical engineering. I don=E2=80=99t kn=
ow if this is right or wrong, but early on, I really looked at software as =
a tool to get something done. But I enjoyed building stuff, so mechanical e=
ngineering seemed like a good path to be able to build physical things, but=
 I really connect that with software.

Of course, there was a lot of software already being used in these engineer=
