Designing Wings at Boeing

*I have some questions about Boeing.*

*JP:* Yeah, great, I knew you=E2=80=99d come with those. It was a very form=
ative experience for me, first time I saw how a big company works and I sta=
rted as an intern, and this was in the middle of my college experience and =
was put on the program, the 7E7 program.

So this was a developmental program basically was designed to be a much mor=
e efficient airplane and much more environmentally friendly. It was this ai=
rplane or the Sonic Cruiser ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boeing_Sonic_Cr=
uiser ) , were the two programs that were being invested in, and it was a p=
retty lucky experience because if you look at airplane programs, they only =
happened once every decade, a major one. Then just through luck, I was able=
 to get onto this program, they just started hiring interns again. Boeing h=
ad gone through a big =E2=80=94 hadn=E2=80=99t hired any engineers for ten =
years, and so this was just coming out of the financial crisis and things l=
ike that, so I was able to get that internship and I was off into the races=
 in the aerospace world.

*I thought you worked on the 787.*

*JP:* The 7E7, and that turned it into the 787.

*Got it.*

*JP:* So that was the very early days before it was really a launch program=
 and officially launched program, and when I came back full-time, they deci=
ded, =E2=80=9CHey, this airplane was worth building.=E2=80=9D So then it be=
came the 787, close the ANA and JAL, launch airlines, and they had purchase=
 orders for a few hundred planes and so that was enough for Boeing to say, =
=E2=80=9CHey, let=E2=80=99s go build some airplanes.=E2=80=9D

*So you worked on the wing specifically?*

*JP:* That=E2=80=99s right. So the project as a mechanical engineer, I was =
originally started on the tails where I was doing structural optimization. =
Today, people would say generative design type of work on the ribs of the t=
ail, was able to get a lot of weight out of the tail on these metal parts a=
nd then I moved to the wing and the wing is the 787. One of the unique attr=
ibutes of it is about 20% more efficient airplane and one of the reasons wh=
y it=E2=80=99s made of carbon fiber.

*Yeah. It moves all over the place, you can see it.*

*JP:* Yeah, so very flexible wing ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Dm5GD3=
E2onlk ) , so if you=E2=80=99ve ever flown it, that=E2=80=99s the final des=
ign that=E2=80=99s on there, I was very involved with that. Of course, a la=
rge engineering team all contributed to this, but I became one of the lead =
engineers to optimize that design and really started combining together sim=
ulation work related to material science.

So carbon fiber has many different ways you can tailor this material, the b=
ig shift was really going from a metal airplane, which is a simple way to t=
hink about it is with metals, the materials, the same strength in all direc=
